          "heading_html": "<p>Understanding Product &nbsp;Recognition</p>",
          "body_html": "<p>Transitioning to open hardware can feel daunting, but you do not need to overhaul your entire operation overnight. <br><br>Join Matty in the video below, to learn how industry leaders approach adoption and why the journey often begins with a <strong>single step</strong>.</p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "type": "image",
          "variant": "text_aside",
          "style": {
            "background_type": "COLOR",
            "background_color": "#f2f2f2",
            "image_opacity": 0.5,
            "image_opacity_color": "#000000",
            "zoom_on_click": true,
            "attached_to_next": false,
            "padding_top": 3,
            "padding_bottom": 3
          },
          "media": {
            "path": "resources/images/ocp-accepted.png",
            "alt": "OCP Accepted.png",
            "source_asset": "OCP Accepted.png",
            "dimensions": {
              "originalWidth": 795,
              "originalHeight": 315
            }
          },
          "body_html": "<p>When you are ready to procure hardware, you will use the <strong>OCP Marketplace</strong>. <br><br>To ensure quality and interoperability, look for the<strong> OCP Accepted badge.&nbsp;</strong>This is the highest tier. A product that is \"OCP Accepted\" meets the official product recognition tier from the Open Compute Project. It indicates that a hardware product (such as a server, rack, or storage drive) complies with an approved OCP contribution such as a specification.</p>"
        },
